Quantum Energy Teleportation provides a testbed for modern ideas involving the inter- 
play between quantum correlations and energy in the quantum thermodynamical regime. 
In this work, we provide a new class of Quantum Energy Teleportation protocols optimized 
for harnessing maximal amounts of correlations between subsystems. We also construct 
new measurement protocols for quantum i elds which provide signif i cant improvements 
for entanglement harvesting. Finally, we construct an ef i cient formalism for computing 
changes in energy due to localized interactions in quantum i eld theory.ChatGPTChatGPTThe abstract of Guillaume Verdon-Akzam's thesis, "Probing Quantum Fields: Measurements and Quantum Energy Teleportation," discusses three key contributions in the realm of quantum physics:Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) Protocols: The thesis introduces a new class of QET protocols, focusing on optimizing them to harness maximum quantum correlations between different subsystems. This development is significant in the study of quantum thermodynamics, where the interplay between quantum correlations and energy is a central theme.Measurement Protocols for Quantum Fields: The work presents new measurement protocols for quantum fields, which offer significant improvements in entanglement harvesting. Entanglement harvesting is the process of extracting quantum entanglement from fields, and these new protocols likely enhance the efficiency and effectiveness of this process.Formalism for Energy Changes in Quantum Field Theory: Finally, the thesis develops an efficient formalism to compute changes in energy due to localized interactions within quantum field theory. This formalism is crucial for understanding how energy behaves at the quantum level, particularly in response to interactions in a quantum field.Overall, the thesis makes substantial contributions to quantum field theory, particularly in understanding and utilizing quantum energy and correlations, as well as improving measurement techniques in this complex field.YouChapter 1 
Introduction 
The relation between energy and information has intrigued physicists for quite some time 
now.Usually, we speak of such a relation in the context of thermodynamics or black 
hole physics. Recently, quite a bit of work has been interested in the thermodynamics of 
spacetime itself[37, 14], and on emergent holographic spacetimes [54]. Understanding the 
relation between energy, information and geometry is the 21st century holy grail of physics. 
The overall focus of this thesis is just that; the interplay between energy and correla- 
tions. We approach the topics from multiple dif f erent angles. 
One of the common themes is the coupling of probe systems to certain subsystems of 
a correlated quantum systems in order to achieve an energetic or information theoretic 
gain. We will cover how measurements, entanglement harvesting, and quantum energy 
teleportation af f ect quantum i elds and harmonic lattices. 
Probes are âwindowsâ into the behaviour of a certain system. They can be very useful 
to understand certain phenomena in quantum i eld theory, as they ef f ectively reduce the 
dimensionality (Hilbert-space-wise) of the problem. They are an indispensable tool for the 
study of Relativistic Quantum Information. 
Thus, because probing i elds is quite important, we develop a theory for the decompo- 
sition of the Hilbert space into âwindowsâ, or rather, algebras of smeared i eld observables. 
See sec. 5.2. One of the most useful results is the expression of the Hamiltonian of the 
i eld with respect to such smeared obseervables. Ef f ectively, multi-page calculations with 
multivariate Gaussian and Fourier integrals simplify to taking a few simple commutators. 
Once we are armed with this tool, we apply it to the study of measurement of such 
smeared observables (5.3.2) using a continuous-variable adaptation of a quantum com- 
puting algorithm known as phase estimation. We introduce the original algorithm in our quantum information background section, while the continuous-variable variant is intro- 
duced in chapter 4. 
In the chapter 3, we introduce the protocol of quantum energy teleportation. We cover 
the basic case of the minimal QET protocol and we write down a general algoithm for QET 
which uses multi-observable correlations in order to optimize the teleportation of energy. 
In chapter 4, we apply this algorithm to a lattice of harmonic oscillators, and later on, in 
chapter 6 we port over this same calculation to QFT, using our Hamiltonian of smeared 
observables formalism. 
Further on, we apply what we learned about the tensor factors of Hilbert space corre- 
sponding to smeared observables to ef f ectively coherently swap quantum information from 
a probe system to a subspace of the i eld. We cover this for a continuous-variable probe 
and also a set of qubits which ef f ectively âdigitizeâ a subspace of the i eld. We then use 
this to harvest entanglement from the vacuum in section 5.4.3. 
Finally, in our future works section, we consider how one could i nd the Schmidt basis, 
i.e. the basis of a Hilbert space for an entangled state across a bipartition, for a quantum 
i eldâs bipartition of the Hilbert space into a spherical region and its complement. By 
adapting some recent litterature [37], we are able to ef f ectively i nd the set of modes 
for the quantum i eld such that the mode decomposition of the state gives the Schmidt 
decomposition.ChatGPTChatGPTChapter 1 of Guillaume Verdon-Akzam's thesis, "Probing Quantum Fields: Measurements and Quantum Energy Teleportation," introduces the central theme of exploring the relationship between energy, information, and correlations in the quantum realm. Here's a summary of the key points:Interplay of Energy, Information, and Geometry: The chapter underscores the importance of understanding the connection between energy, information, and geometry, considering it the "21st century holy grail of physics." This connection is particularly relevant in thermodynamics, black hole physics, spacetime thermodynamics, and emergent holographic spacetimes.Probing Correlated Quantum Systems: The thesis focuses on how probing systems, such as measurements, entanglement harvesting, and quantum energy teleportation, can interact with and affect correlated quantum systems, including quantum fields and harmonic lattices. Probes serve as tools for understanding phenomena in quantum field theory and are vital in the study of Relativistic Quantum Information.Decomposition of Hilbert Space: A significant part of the chapter is dedicated to developing a theory for decomposing the Hilbert space into "windows" or algebras of smeared field observables. This approach simplifies complex calculations and is crucial for studying quantum field measurements.Application of Quantum Computing Algorithms: The thesis applies a continuous-variable adaptation of the quantum computing algorithm known as phase estimation to the measurement of smeared observables, introducing a novel approach in Chapter 4.Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET): Chapter 3 introduces the concept of QET, covering the basic protocol and a general algorithm that optimizes energy teleportation using multi-observable correlations. This concept is applied to a lattice of harmonic oscillators and quantum field theory (QFT) using the developed formalism.Entanglement Harvesting from the Vacuum: The thesis explores the use of tensor factors of Hilbert space corresponding to smeared observables for coherently swapping quantum information from a probe system to a subspace of the field. This includes harvesting entanglement from the vacuum.Future Work and Schmidt Decomposition: The chapter concludes with future work considerations, including finding the Schmidt basis for a quantum field's bipartition of the Hilbert space. This involves adapting recent literature to identify modes in the quantum field for an effective Schmidt decomposition.Overall, Chapter 1 sets the stage for a detailed exploration of the interplay between energy, information, and geometry in quantum fields, employing innovative techniques and algorithms.YouDefine the difficult termsChatGPTChatGPTCertainly! Let's define some of the complex terms from the chapter summary:Quantum Field Theory (QFT): A theoretical framework that combines classical field theory, special relativity, and quantum mechanics. It's used to construct physical models of subatomic particles and their interactions.Hilbert Space: A mathematical concept used in quantum mechanics. It's an abstract vector space equipped with an inner product, providing a framework for discussing the quantum states of a system.Entanglement Harvesting: The process of extracting quantum entanglement from a quantum field. Entangled particles are those whose states are interdependent, no matter the distance separating them.Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET): A theoretical concept where energy is transmitted across a distance without moving the physical particles themselves. This relies on quantum entanglement and measurements.Smeared Field Observables: In quantum field theory, observables are physical quantities that can be measured. 'Smeared' refers to a technique where these quantities are averaged or integrated over a region of space-time, helping to deal with infinities in quantum field theory.Phase Estimation Algorithm: A quantum algorithm used for estimating the phase (or eigenvalue) of an eigenstate of a unitary operator. It's crucial in many quantum computing applications.Continuous-Variable System: In quantum information, this refers to systems where observables, like position and momentum, can take on a continuous range of values, as opposed to discrete variables like in quantum bits (qubits).Schmidt Decomposition: A mathematical form used in quantum mechanics to describe the state of a composite quantum system as a sum of product states. It's useful for understanding entanglement.Quantum Information Theory: A branch of science and mathematics that deals with how quantum systems can be used for storing, transmitting, and processing information.Relativistic Quantum Information: A field of study that combines quantum information theory with the principles of relativity, often dealing with how information is processed in the context of space-time and gravity.These terms are fundamental to understanding advanced concepts in quantum physics and quantum information science.YouBackground: Quantum Information 
In this chapter we provide a brief review of a few concepts from Quantum Information 
theory and Quantum Computing which are essential for understanding the contents of this 
thesis. 
Most of the content on quantum information theory and quantum computing covered 
in this chapter can be found in Nielsen & Chuang [51] and Wilde [72]. For the Gaussian 
state formalism, we mainly use work by Adesso [1]. For quantum error correction, we use 
Gottesmanâs work [24]. 
2.1Quantum Information Theory Essentials 
It will be assumed that the readers of this thesis have a good background on the basics of 
quantum information theory. Thus section is mostly a collection of useful formulas which 
we include for convenience. 
2.1.1Information Theoretic Measures 
Shannon Entropy 
Consider a random classical variable X with a certain probability distribution over out- 
comes p(x) = Pr(x = X), then the measure of entropy, sometimes called the Shannon 
3 
entropy, is def i ned as1 H(X) â¡ X 
x âp(x)log(p(x)).(2.1) 
In some sense the entropy is a measure of uncertainty in a random variable. 
Here is a rough sketch of how this concept applies to certain situations: say we have an 
alphabet X and for any given message there is a probability p(x) that a given letter X is 
x. Then, if we consider how one could optimally encode this alphabet as binary, then we 
can assign more bits to less likely letters, and less bits to the more frequently used letters. 
If we want the same number of bits for each letter on average, since they occur at a rate of 
1/p(x), and n bits can cover 2nletters, then we use n = log2(1/p(x)) bits per letter. Then, 
the entropy is simply the expectation value of the number of bits, P 
xp(x)log2(1/p(x)), 
hence, asymptotically, we hit a rate of transmission of information equal to the Shannon 
entropy of our variable.ChatGPTChatGPTIn this section of the thesis, the author provides an overview of essential concepts in Quantum Information Theory and Quantum Computing, which are critical for understanding the thesis. It serves as a collection of useful formulas and concepts for easy reference.2.1.1 Information Theoretic MeasuresShannon EntropyDefinition: Shannon Entropy is a measure of the uncertainty or the amount of information in a random variable. It's defined for a classical random variable XXX with a probability distribution p(x)p(x)p(x) (where p(x)=Pr(x=X)p(x) = \text{Pr}(x = X)p(x)=Pr(x=X)) as:H(X)=ââxp(x)logâ¡(p(x))H(X) = -\sum_{x} p(x) \log(p(x))H(X)=ââxâp(x)log(p(x))Application: This concept is applied to information encoding. For example, in an alphabet XXX, each letter xxx appears with a probability p(x)p(x)p(x). In optimal binary encoding, less frequent letters are assigned more bits, and more common letters are assigned fewer bits. The number of bits per letter is logâ¡2(1/p(x))\log_2(1/p(x))log2â(1/p(x)). The entropy represents the expected number of bits per letter. It implies that the rate of information transmission asymptotically approaches the Shannon entropy of the variable.This overview sets the stage for more advanced discussions in the thesis, situating Shannon Entropy and other quantum information concepts as foundational for understanding the interplay between quantum measurements, energy, and information.YouVon Neumann entropy

it is the negative of the conditional quantum entropy, that is, the negative of the entropy

distillable means that the version of the protocol used to distill entanglement used two-way 
communication.ChatGPTChatGPTThe section on entanglement in the thesis provides insights into the quantification and understanding of entanglement in bipartite quantum systems.Entanglement EntropyDefinition: For a bipartite pure state ÏAB=â£Ïâ©â¨Ïâ£AB\rho_{AB} = |\psi\rangle \langle \psi|_{AB}ÏABâ=â£Ïâ©â¨Ïâ£ABâ, the entanglement entropy is defined as the Von Neumann entropy of either of the marginal states (subsystems A or B). Note that any quantum channel can always be represented as unitary on a larger Hilbert

These concepts are crucial for understanding quantum measurements and their effects on quantum states.2.1.2 MeasurementPOVM (Positive Operator-Valued Measure)Definition: A POVM is a set of measurement operators {Aj}j\{A_j\}_j{Ajâ}jâ that satisfy the completeness relation:âjAjâ Aj=I\sum_j A_j^\dagger A_j = IâjâAjâ âAjâ=IHere, Ajâ A_j^\daggerAjâ â is the adjoint (conjugate transpose) of AjA_jAjâ, and III is the identity operator.Measurement Process: When a POVM is applied to a quantum state represented by a density operator Ï\rhoÏ, the probability of obtaining outcome jjj is given by:tr(AjÏAjâ )\text{tr}(A_j \rho A_j^\dagger)tr(AjâÏAjâ â)The state of the system after the measurement (if outcome jjj is obtained) collapses to:AjÏAjâ tr(AjÏAjâ )\frac{A_j \rho A_j^\dagger}{\text{tr}(A_j \rho A_j^\dagger)}tr(AjâÏAjâ â)AjâÏAjâ ââApplication: POVMs represent a more general form of quantum measurements compared to the traditional projective measurements, allowing for a wider range of measurement outcomes.Stinespring and Kraus FormKraus Form: This form describes the action of a quantum channel on a state Ï\rhoÏ as a sum of operations by different Kraus operators AjA_jAjâ:ÏââjAjÏAjâ \rho \rightarrow \sum_j A_j \rho A_j^\daggerÏââjâAjâÏAjâ âThis is often used to describe the evolution of quantum states in open quantum systems.Stinespring Dilation: Any quantum channel can be represented as a unitary operation on a larger Hilbert space that includes ancillary inputs. Some of the outputs are then traced out (ignored), which is known as Stinespring dilation. This form is not necessarily unique and provides a way to visualize non-unitary quantum channels as part of a larger unitary process.Application in Quantum Algorithms: These forms are particularly relevant for understanding the implementation of quantum algorithms like phase estimation. For Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET), instead of directly employing the POVM formalism, the approach involves Stinespring dilation to the phase estimation algorithm.These concepts in quantum measurement theory play a pivotal role in understanding how quantum states are affected by measurements and how information is extracted from them in quantum computing and information processing.You2.2Qudits & The Quantum Fourier Transform 
2.2.1Qudits 
Qubit Paulis 
Pauli matrices play a central role for qubits. They span the Lie algebra3su(2) , and can be 
seen as a set of unitary gates which form a basis for the space of 2Ã2 Hermitian matrices4. 
Unfortunately, for higher dimensions, there is not a single set of matrices which can 
play all these roles. In this section we will review some of the generalizations of the Pauli 
matrices which individually accomplish these roles for Hilbert spaces of dimension d > 2. 
We begin with the Heisenberg-Weyl group. 
Heisenberg-Weyl 
Let us consider a i rst set of generalized Pauli matrices, often called the Weyl (or Heisenberg- 
Weyl operators [9, 70], these act on the Hilbert space H = Cd. The generalized Pauli Z

While a qubit can be in a state of 0, 1, or a superposition of both, a qudit has ddd states (where ddd is greater than 2). It's a more general form of a quantum state.Generalized Pauli Matrices for Qudits:Clock Matrix (Z): This matrix changes the phase of each state in a qudit.Shift Matrix (X): This matrix "shifts" each state to the next one. For example, it turns state 0 into state 1, state 1 into state 2, and so on, wrapping around back to state 0 after the last state.Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT):What It Does: The QFT is a transformation used in quantum computing that changes the way a qudit is described, from one set of states to another.Relation to Shift Matrix: The QFT can transform the Shift Matrix into the Clock Matrix. This is a bit like changing the perspective from which you view the states of a qudit.Eigenstates and Eigendecomposition:Eigenstates of X: These are special states that, when the Shift Matrix is applied to them, they simply change by a factor (like getting multiplied by a number) instead of getting shifted.Eigendecomposition of X: This is a way of expressing the Shift Matrix as a combination of its eigenstates and the effects they have.Heisenberg-Weyl Group:This is a mathematical concept that encompasses the Clock and Shift matrices. It represents a set of operations you can perform on the states of a qudit.In simpler terms, the section describes how qudits work in quantum computing, especially focusing on how certain matrices (like the Clock and Shift matrices) are used to manipulate them. The Quantum Fourier Transform is a crucial tool that allows us to change our perspective on these states and is vital for many quantum computing operations.YouA useful property is that the linear combinations of elements in the Heisenberg-Weyl

Let's simplify these concepts:Heisenberg-Weyl Group and dÃdd \times ddÃd Matrices:Spanning of Matrices: Elements of the Heisenberg-Weyl group can be combined to form any dÃdd \times ddÃd matrix. This is significant because it means any operation on a qudit can be represented using elements from this group.Traceless and Unitary: Most of these matrices are traceless (except the identity matrix) and unitary (matrices that, when multiplied by their conjugate transpose, result in the identity matrix). Let's break this down:Spin vs. Spin-like GeneratorsHermitian Generators of Unitary Matrices:Background: The Heisenberg-Weyl matrices (like the Z matrix) are unitary but not self-adjoint (Hermitian). However, as unitary matrices, they are generated by Hermitian operators.Z Matrix Generator: The Z matrix (phase matrix) is generated by a spin-like operator, denoted as JJJ, which is similar to the spin operator in quantum mechanics. This generator is defined as:J=âk=0dâ1kâ£kâ©â¨kâ£,wheree2ÏiJ/d=ZJ = \sum_{k=0}^{d-1} k |k\rangle\langle k|, \quad \text{where} \quad e^{2\pi iJ/d} = ZJ=âk=0dâ1âkâ£kâ©â¨kâ£,wheree2ÏiJ/d=ZComparison with Quantum Mechanics Spin Operators:Spin-like Operator: The operator JJJ can be thought of as analogous to the spin operator for a "spin-(dâ1)/2(d-1)/2(dâ1)/2" particle. In quantum mechanics, spin operators represent angular momentum in quantum states.Relation to JzJ_zJzâ Operator: If s=(dâ1)/2s = (d - 1)/2s=(dâ1)/2, then JJJ can be related to the z-component of the spin operator JzJ_zJzâ in quantum mechanics, but with an additional term:J~=Jâ(dâ1)2I\tilde{J} = J - \frac{(d-1)}{2} IJ~=Jâ2(dâ1)âIHere, III is the identity matrix.Phase Difference in Unitary Exponentiation:Extra Phase: When using J~\tilde{J}J~ instead of JJJ for unitary exponentiation, there is an additional phase factor. This becomes significant in contexts involving interactions.Practical Use: In quantum computing contexts involving qudits, when referring to a "spin-like" operator, it's actually J~\tilde{J}J~ that's used, not JJJ.Distinction from Quantum Mechanics Operators:X Matrix and Jx Operator: The logarithm of the shift matrix XXX (from the Heisenberg-Weyl group) is unrelated to the x-component of the spin operator (JxJ_xJxâ) in quantum mechanics.Raising Operator vs. X Operator: The X operator differs from the quantum mechanical raising operator J+J_+J+â. While J+J_+J+â shifts quantum states up until the top eigenvalue and then annihilates the state, the X operator cycles the states back to the lowest eigenvalue after reaching the top.This section emphasizes the nuanced differences and parallels between spin operators in traditional quantum mechanics and their counterparts in the study of qudits. Understanding these distinctions is crucial for correctly applying quantum mechanical concepts to higher-dimensional quantum systems like qudits.YouSome metaphors or analogies to explain it.ChatGPTChatGPTCertainly! Let's use some metaphors and analogies to explain these complex quantum concepts:1. Spin vs. Spin-like GeneratorsMusic Notes and Octaves Analogy:Imagine the Z matrix as a keyboard where each key represents a different note. Pressing a key (applying the Z matrix) changes the pitch (phase) of the music note (quantum state). The J operator is like the mechanism inside the keyboard that causes this change in pitch. Just like each key on the keyboard corresponds to a note, each level in the J operator corresponds to a different state in the Z matrix.The spin-like operator J~\tilde{J}J~ is akin to a modified keyboard where the keys are slightly detuned. When you press a key on this modified keyboard, you still get a musical note but with a slightly different pitch compared to the standard keyboard. In quantum terms, using J~\tilde{J}J~ instead of JJJ adds an extra phase (like a slight detuning).2. Quantum Mechanics Spin Operators vs. Heisenberg-Weyl Group OperatorsLibrary Bookshelf Analogy:Think of quantum states as books arranged on a circular bookshelf. The X operator in the Heisenberg-Weyl group acts like a mechanism that moves each book to the next position on the shelf. Once a book reaches the end of the shelf, it gets moved back to the beginning, creating a continuous cycle.On the other hand, the quantum mechanical raising operator J+J_+J+â is like a librarian who moves books up the shelf, one position at a time. However, when reaching the top, instead of moving the book back to the bottom, the librarian removes it from the shelf entirely (annihilating the top state).3. Unitary Matrices and Their Hermitian GeneratorsClock Hands Analogy:The unitary matrices in the Heisenberg-Weyl group can be thought of as the hands of a clock. The motion of the clock hands (changes in the quantum state) is smooth and continuous (reflecting the unitary nature of the transformation).The Hermitian generators (like JJJ and J~\tilde{J}J~) are like the gears inside the clock that drive the movement of the hands. These gears determine how fast and in what direction the hands move. The extra phase introduced by J~\tilde{J}J~ is like adjusting the gears slightly, causing the clock hands to move at a slightly different pace.These metaphors help to visualize and understand the abstract concepts of spin and spin-like generators, the behavior of quantum states under different operators, and the nature of unitary transformations in the quantum realm.2 / 2YouA minute ago you used musical chairs as an analogy, but I cut you off.ChatGPTChatGPTOf course, let's revisit the musical chairs analogy to explain these quantum concepts:Musical Chairs Analogy for the Heisenberg-Weyl Group and Spin OperatorsThe X Operator (Shift Matrix) and Musical Chairs:Imagine a game of musical chairs where each chair represents a different quantum state in the qudit system. The X operator acts like the music in this game. When the music plays (the operator is applied), everyone moves to the next chair in the circle. Once a player reaches the last chair and the music plays again, they move back to the first chair, creating a continuous loop. This is like the cyclic nature of the X operator, shifting states in a loop.The Z Operator (Clock Matrix) and Changing Music:In the same game, let's say the type of music playing (classical, jazz, rock, etc.) affects how the players feel while sitting in their chairs (their quantum state). The Z operator is like changing the genre of music, altering the "state" (mood) of the players in each chair. The J operator is the DJ's control panel, determining what music plays.The Spin-like Operator J~\tilde{J}J~ and a Modified Musical Chairs Game:Now, consider a variation of musical chairs where, in addition to moving to the next chair, each player also wears a hat that changes color every time the music plays. This hat-changing represents the additional phase introduced by the spin-like operator J~\tilde{J}J~. So, while the basic movement (spin) is the same, the added effect (phase change) slightly alters the game's dynamics.Quantum Mechanical Raising Operator J+J_+J+â and Limited Chairs:In contrast to the circular musical chairs, the quantum mechanical raising operator J+J_+J+â behaves more like a line of chairs where players move up one chair at a time. But, if a player reaches the last chair and the music plays, they leave the game (annihilation of the state) instead of going back to the first chair. This reflects the non-cyclical nature of J+J_+J+â in quantum mechanics.Through this musical chairs analogy, we can visualize the cyclic behavior of the X operator, the state-altering effect of the Z operator and its generator, the added complexity introduced by the spin-like operator J~\tilde{J}J~, and the linear, non-cyclical action of the quantum mechanical raising operator J+J_+J+â.You2.2.2The Quantum Fourier transform for qubits

Let's simplify these concepts:2.2.2 The Quantum Fourier Transform for QubitsQubits Forming a Qudit Space:Large Hilbert Space: When you combine the Hilbert spaces of nnn qubits (each qubit has a 2-dimensional Hilbert space), you get an exponentially large combined space, equivalent to C2n\mathbb{C}^{2^n}C2n.Qubit to Qudit: You can represent a qudit (a quantum system with ddd states) using only logâ¡2(d)\log_2(d)log2â(d) qubits due to this exponential increase in dimensionality.Mapping in QFT for Qudits:Qudit Representation: In a qudit system, the QFT maps state â£jâ©|j\rangleâ£jâ© to a superposition of all possible states with specific phase factors.Qubit Equivalent: For nnn qubits representing a 2n2^n2n-dimensional qudit, this transformation is represented differently. It involves a combination of simpler states, each modified by a phase factor depending on their position in the binary representation of jjj.Implementation of QFT in Qubits:Polynomial Number of Gates: The QFT for qubits can be implemented using a polynomial number of quantum gates, primarily Hadamard gates (for creating superpositions) and controlled rotations (for adding phase differences).Controlled Phase Gates: These gates involve a control qubit and a target qubit, where the state of the control qubit determines the operation applied to the target. The operation includes rotations which add phase shifts, crucial for the QFT.Tuning for QFT:Adjusting Parameters: By adjusting the parameter Î¸\thetaÎ¸ in the controlled phase gates depending on which qubits are interacting, the QFT can be achieved. This involves careful control of the phase shifts introduced in each step.Efficiency in Emulating Qudits:Efficient Emulation: With sufficient control, a set of qubits can efficiently emulate a qudit, allowing for complex quantum computations using a manageable number of qubits.Metaphor for UnderstandingThink of a qubit system like a choir. Each singer (qubit) can sing either a low or high note (binary state). When they sing together, they can create a vast range of harmonies (the large Hilbert space). The QFT is like a conductor who arranges the choir to sing a complex piece of music (quantum state transformation) where each singer's note affects the others' (entanglement and phase relationships). This coordinated effort allows the choir to perform sophisticated compositions (complex quantum operations) with just a few singers (qubits), rather than needing one singer for each note in the piece (a direct representation of a qudit state).You2.3Phase estimation Algorithm 
The phase estimation algorithm [51] involves performing a measurement on a certain target

Let's break it down with a simpler explanation and an analogy:2.3 Phase Estimation AlgorithmBasic ConceptPurpose: The phase estimation algorithm is used to measure the phase (or eigenvalue) of a quantum state. It's particularly useful when you want to understand how a quantum state changes when a certain operation (represented by a unitary matrix) is applied to it.How It WorksSetup: You start with a set of ancillary qubits (helpers) and a target system (the main qubit or qubits you're interested in).Creating Superposition: The ancillary qubits are put into a superposition of all possible states using Hadamard gates. This is like setting up a row of spinning coins where each coin is spinning in a way that it's both heads and tails at the same time.Controlled-Unitaries: Then, you apply controlled-unitary operations. These operations are controlled by the ancillary qubits and affect the target system. The unitary operation encodes the phase information onto the ancillary qubits.Entangled State: The interaction between the ancillary and target qubits creates an entangled state, where the state of the ancillary qubits depends on the phase of the target system.Applying Inverse Quantum Fourier Transform: After applying the controlled-unitary operations, the inverse Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT) is applied to the ancillary qubits. This step is like translating the complex quantum information into a more readable form.Measurement: Finally, by measuring the ancillary qubits, you can find out the phase of the target system. The result is the phase information encoded in a binary form.Circuit Diagram DescriptionThe circuit diagram for this algorithm shows the sequence of operations: initialization of ancillary qubits, application of Hadamard gates, controlled-unitaries, inverse QFT, and finally the measurement.Analogy: Detecting a Secret TuneImagine you're trying to figure out a secret tune played on a piano, but you can only use a set of tuning forks (ancillary qubits). Each tuning fork can resonate with a certain note (phase) of the tune. You start by setting all the forks vibrating a little (superposition). Then, you play the secret tune (apply the unitary operation) while the forks are near the piano. Each fork picks up a certain part of the tune based on its natural frequency (phase kickback). Finally, you analyze how each tuning fork vibrated (inverse QFT and measurement) to decode the tune's notes (phase information of the quantum state).YouThe phase estimation algorithm is an important algorithm in quantum computation that involves measuring the phase of a quantum state. It utilizes ancillary qubits and a unitary interaction to perform a measurement known as a POVM (Positive Operator-Valued Measure). The algorithm and its variants are commonly used in various quantum computing applications.

The algorithm is based on the property of qudits, which are quantum systems with d levels. In particular, it relies on the property that a phase matrix Z, defined as Z = Pdâ1âj=0 e^(2Ïij/d) |jihj|, gets converted to a cyclical shift of the state X = Pdâ1âj=0 |[j + 1]dihj|. Here, |jihjâ© represents the computational basis state of the qudit.

In the algorithm, a controlled-phase gate is used, similar to the one used in the quantum Fourier transform. Suppose we have t ancillary qubits, and instead of using the Pauli phase gate (Ïz) as the controlled unitary, we use a general observable O in the target register. The unitaries have the form U = exp(-i2Ï/d |1ih1| â O + |0ih0| â I + |1ih1| â e^(-i2ÏO/d)). If the control register is in a uniform phaseless superposition of computational basis states (an X eigenstate of eigenvalue 1, denoted as |+i), and the target register is in an eigenstate |Ïi of O with eigenvalue Ï, then applying the unitary U results in an entangled state.

By scaling up this intuition, we consider the unitary Ut = â(t-1)k=0 exp(-i2Ïi2^k |1ih1|^k â O), which acts on a tensor product of |+iâ© states. If we apply this unitary to |+iâ©ât â |Ïiâ©, we obtain a state that can be recognized as |xÏi, where xÏ is the binary representation of the phase Ï. By applying the inverse quantum Fourier transform (Fâ ) to go back to the computational basis, we obtain |Ïiâ|Ïiâ©. Therefore, by measuring the control registers, we can determine the binary representation of the phase Ï.

The circuit diagram for the quantum phase estimation algorithm is shown in Figure 2.1. The target register represents the state on m qubits that we want to estimate the phase of. The ancillary qubits are initialized in the computational default state. The algorithm consists of several steps: 
1. Apply a transversal Hadamard gate to the ancillary qubits to put them in a uniform phaseless superposition of all bit strings.
2. Apply the controlled-unitaries, which allow the phase to "kick back" from the target to the control.
3. Apply the inverse Fourier transform (Fâ ) to convert the acquired phase into bit flips.
4. Perform a projective measurement in the standard basis to obtain the binary representation of the phase.

This algorithm is widely used in quantum computation and has applications in various quantum algorithms and protocols, such as quantum simulation, quantum factoring, and quantum error correction.ChatGPTChatGPTYour summary of the Phase Estimation Algorithm (PEA) in quantum computation is quite thorough. It is designed to measure the phase (a unique characteristic) of a quantum state.Utilization of Qudits and Ancillary Qubits:Qudits: Quantum systems with ddd levels. This property is essential for the algorithm's function.Controlled-Phase Gate:A key component of the algorithm, it differs from the standard quantum Fourier transform by using a general observable OOO in the target register.The operation creates an entangled state between the ancillary qubits and the target system.Algorithm Steps:Initialization: Ancillary qubits are prepared in a uniform superposition.Controlled-Unitaries: Apply operations that depend on the target system's state.Inverse Quantum Fourier Transform: This step is crucial for translating the quantum information into a measurable form.Measurement: The final step gives the binary representation of the phase Ï.Circuit Diagram Explanation:Demonstrates the sequence of operations in the PEA, showing the process from initialization to measurement.Significance: The PEA is fundamental for accurately measuring quantum states, a cornerstone operation in many advanced quantum algorithms and protocols.Your explanation does a great job of outlining the technical details and the overall process of the Phase Estimation Algorithm in quantum computing.YouSome more detailed explanation of the difficult terms.ChatGPTChatGPTAbsolutely, let's break down some of the complex terms used in the Phase Estimation Algorithm (PEA) for a clearer understanding:Qudit:A generalization of a qubit. While a qubit is a quantum system with 2 states (like 0 and 1), a qudit has ddd states. Think of a qubit as a coin (heads or tails) and a qudit as a dice with ddd faces.Ancillary Qubits:These are additional qubits used in a quantum algorithm alongside the main qubits of interest. They are like helpers or assistants in an experiment, used to facilitate the process and often to hold interim results.Phase Matrix (Z) and Shift Matrix (X):Phase Matrix (Z): A quantum operation that changes the phase of a quantum state. For a qudit, it's represented by a matrix where each diagonal element corresponds to a different phase.Shift Matrix (X): This operation shifts the state of a qudit to the next state in a cyclic manner. In the context of a dice, it's like rolling the dice to the next number.Controlled-Phase Gate:A quantum gate where the action on one (target) qubit or qudit depends on the state of another (control) qubit. It's a bit like a conditional command: "If the control qubit is in state 1, then apply this operation to the target qubit."General Observable (O):In quantum mechanics, observables are physical quantities that can be measured, like position or momentum. In PEA, a general observable refers to a specific property or aspect of the quantum state you're interested in measuring.Entangled State:A key feature of quantum mechanics where the state of one quantum particle is dependent on the state of another, regardless of the distance between them. In the PEA, the ancillary and target qubits become entangled, meaning their states are interconnected.Unitary Operation:An operation in quantum mechanics that evolves the state of a quantum system while preserving probabilities. These operations are reversible, which is a fundamental property in quantum computing.Inverse Quantum Fourier Transform:The Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT) is a quantum version of the classical Fourier Transform and is used to convert between different quantum states. The inverse QFT essentially reverses this process, converting the quantum information back into a more classical form that can be easily read.Binary Representation of Phase Ï:After the PEA, the measurement results are read out in binary form, representing the phase Ï. This is similar to reading a binary code (like 0101) that encodes the value of the phase.Each of these elements plays a critical role in the execution and success of the Phase Estimation Algorithm, a cornerstone in many quantum computing applications.You2.3.2Information gain

The entanglement entropy, given by S_AB = -âj |Î»j|^2 log2(|Î»j|^2), quantifies the amount of information gained by the ancillary system about the target. It is equal to the Shannon entropy of the measurement outcomes if we were to directly measure the observable O of the target register through a projective measurement. Thus, the entanglement entropy represents the information gained about the target.

When we apply the phase estimation algorithm to a state |Ïâ© for which Ï is not an integer (Ï â Z), we obtain an approximate value |ËÏâ© instead of the exact value |Ïâ©. The accuracy of the approximation depends on the number of bits used in the algorithm. The more bits we use (larger t), the wider the spread of the probe state, and consequently, when we apply the Fourier transform, the sharper the Fourier transform becomes.

To obtain an accurate n-bit readout, we need to use t qubits, where t > n, to run the algorithm. However, the readout of the noisy t - n qubits at the end may be inaccurate and can be ignored. It has been shown that to achieve an accurate n-bit readout with a probability of success greater than (1 - Îµ), we need to use at least t = n + d log(2 + (2Îµ)^-1)e qubits, where d is the dimension of the qudit. This equation (2.42) provides an estimation of the number of qubits required for accurate phase estimation.

In this thesis, the systems encountered have infinite and continuous spectra. In most cases, continuous-variable variants of the phase estimation algorithm are used to handle continuous spectra. Note that performing a controlled gate, then projectively measuring the control register 
in the standard basis, or the inverse order of these two are equivalent. this is known as 
the principle of deferred measurement [51]. That is, a classical controlled gate with the 
control being the result of a measurement versus a quantum control gate followed by a 
measurement yield the same i nal state.
There is also the principle of implicit measurement [51], which states that for any 
register that is not used after a certain point in the circuit, we can assume that it was 
measured. UU 
= 
Figure 2.2: A measurement followed by a classical controlled unitary dependent on that 
measurement (left) is equivalent to a quantum controlled unitary followed by a measure- 
ment. In other words, measurements commute with controls. Note the double line 
signif i es classical information (e.g. output of a measurement) while the single line means 
quantum information.ChatGPTChatGPTIn this section, the thesis explains two important principles in quantum computing: the principle of deferred measurement and the principle of implicit measurement. Let's break these down with analogies:2.3.3 Deferred & Implicit MeasurementsDeferred Measurement PrincipleConcept: The principle of deferred measurement states that the order of measurement and controlled operations can be interchanged without affecting the final state of the system. This means a measurement followed by a controlled operation based on that measurement is equivalent to a controlled operation followed by the measurement.Analogy: Think of it like baking a cake (the quantum state). You have two steps: checking the recipe (measurement) and then adjusting the ingredients based on that (controlled operation), or mixing the ingredients first and then checking if it matches the recipe. In the end, you still get the same cake.Implicit Measurement PrincipleConcept: This principle suggests that any part of a quantum system (register) that is not used after a certain point in a quantum circuit can be considered as having been measured. This is because its future state does not influence the rest of the system.Analogy: Imagine you're painting a picture with watercolors. Once you've finished painting a certain area and you don't plan to add anything more to it, it's as if that part is "set" or "measured". Even though you haven't explicitly sealed it with a varnish (actual measurement), its state is no longer influencing the rest of the painting.Circuit Diagram InterpretationIn the provided circuit diagram (Figure 2.2), it illustrates that a measurement followed by a classical control (based on the measurement outcome) is equivalent to a quantum control followed by a measurement. This is a visual representation of the deferred measurement principle. The double line represents classical information flow (e.g., the output of a measurement), while the single line denotes quantum information.These principles are crucial in quantum computing for optimizing quantum circuits and understanding the interplay between quantum and classical information. They help in simplifying complex quantum operations and in making efficient use of quantum resources.YouThe principle of deferred measurement states that performing a controlled gate followed by a projective measurement on the control register is equivalent to performing the measurement first and then applying the classical controlled gate based on the measurement outcome. In other words, a classical controlled gate with the control being the result of a measurement and a quantum controlled gate followed by a measurement yield the same final state. This principle allows for flexibility in the order of operations in a quantum circuit.

Additionally, the principle of implicit measurement states that if a register is not used or accessed after a certain point in the circuit, we can assume that it has been measured. In other words, we can treat the unobserved register as if it has undergone a measurement. This principle simplifies the analysis of quantum circuits by allowing us to consider the unobserved registers as if they have already been measured.

The concept of deferred measurement and implicit measurement is illustrated in Figure 2.2 of the thesis. The figure shows that a measurement followed by a classical controlled unitary dependent on that measurement is equivalent to a quantum controlled unitary followed by a measurement. The double line represents classical information (e.g., the output of a measurement), while the single line represents quantum information. The diagram emphasizes that measurements commute with controls in quantum circuits.ChatGPTChatGPTYou have accurately summarized the principles of deferred measurement and implicit measurement in quantum computing. Let's highlight the key aspects of these principles for a comprehensive understanding:Principle of Deferred MeasurementCore Idea: This principle allows for the interchangeability of measurement and control operations in a quantum circuit without changing the final state.Operational Flexibility: It provides flexibility in designing quantum circuits, as the sequence of measurement and control operations can be adjusted according to convenience or efficiency.Equivalence of Sequences: Whether you measure first and then apply a controlled gate based on that measurement, or apply a controlled gate followed by measurement, the outcome remains the same.Impact on Circuit Design: This principle is particularly useful in simplifying quantum circuit designs and in theoretical analyses where deferring measurements can lead to clearer understanding of the quantum operations.Principle of Implicit MeasurementUnobserved Registers: If a part of the quantum circuit (a register) is not used in subsequent operations, it can be treated as if it were measured.Simplification in Analysis: This principle simplifies the analysis and interpretation of quantum circuits by reducing the need to explicitly consider every part of the system.Assumption of Measurement: Even if an actual measurement is not performed, registers not influencing the rest of the circuit can be assumed to have been measured.Figure 2.2: Illustration of the PrinciplesVisual Representation: The figure demonstrates how a measurement followed by a classical control based on the measurement is equivalent to a quantum control followed by a measurement.Differentiation of Information Types: The diagram uses double lines to represent classical information (resulting from measurements) and single lines for quantum information (quantum states and operations).These principles are foundational in quantum computing, allowing for more efficient and streamlined quantum circuit designs. They also reflect the unique interplay between quantum and classical information in quantum algorithms.YouApplications to QET 
Thus, if we perform the phase estimation algorithm with a certain control register (the 
ancillary register) and then use this registerâs measurement result as the classical control 
for a subsequent controlled unitary, then we can defer the measurement to the end of 
the circuit, and replace the classical control with a quantum controlled unitary operation. 
Furthermore, one the measurement is deferred to the end of the circuit, there is no need 
to actually carry it out. 
Thus, for the phase estimation followed by a controlled unitary combination, we can 
let go of the measurement altogether and replace the circuit elements with their coherent 
counterpart. 
This is exactly what we will do for quantum energy teleportation; as we will see, this 
protocol relies on a measurement, followed by a classically controlled unitary dependent 
on the measurement. In this way, the protocol is LOCC; involves local operations and 
classical communication. 
In our treatment of quantum energy teleportation, we will use the alternate, but, as 
justif i ed above, equivalent version of the protocol, which is entirely coherent. Instead of 
using a POVM, we model these measurements via phase estimation and an ancillary system. 

Following this, instead of classical information being transferred from the measurement site 
to the second target site, we transfer quantum information and apply a controlled unitary, 
no measurement needed.ChatGPTChatGPTThe application of the principles of deferred and implicit measurement in Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) is an innovative approach to streamline the process. Let's break down how these principles are utilized:Application of Deferred Measurement in QETInitial Process: In the standard QET protocol, the process begins with a phase estimation algorithm using an ancillary register. The outcome of this register's measurement is then used as a classical control for a subsequent controlled unitary operation.Deferring the Measurement: By applying the principle of deferred measurement, this process can be restructured. The measurement of the ancillary register, initially crucial for the classical control, can be deferred to the end of the quantum circuit.Replacing Classical Control: With the measurement deferred, the classical control can be replaced with a quantum controlled unitary operation. This step retains the coherence of the quantum state throughout the process.Eliminating the Need for Actual MeasurementCoherent Counterpart: When the measurement is deferred to the end, there's often no need to actually perform it, especially if the information it was supposed to provide is no longer necessary for subsequent operations.Simplification of Circuit: This allows for replacing certain circuit elements with their coherent counterparts, maintaining the quantum state's integrity and potentially simplifying the circuit.Implications for QETLOCC Protocol: The original QET protocol involves Local Operations and Classical Communication (LOCC), where a measurement is followed by a classically controlled unitary dependent on that measurement.Coherent Version of QET: In the revised approach, instead of using a Positive Operator-Valued Measure (POVM) and then transmitting classical information, the entire process is kept quantum coherent. Phase estimation and an ancillary system model the measurements.Quantum Information Transfer: Rather than transferring classical information from the measurement site to the target, quantum information is transferred directly. A controlled unitary operation is applied without the need for actual measurement.SummaryIn essence, the application of deferred and implicit measurement principles in QET allows for a more efficient and coherent quantum process. By deferring measurements and maintaining quantum coherence, the protocol becomes streamlined, potentially increasing its efficacy and simplicity. This approach exemplifies the power of quantum coherence in enhancing quantum communication protocols like QET.You2.4Continuous Variable Quantum Information

Quantum Error correction is a mathematical theory which describes how to hide quantum 
information in certain subspaces of a Hilbert space. Although we will not be treating this 
topic directly in the main body of the thesis, we draw multiple parallels with concepts 
underlying work that will appear later in this thesis. 
2.5.1From Hamiltonians to Subspaces 
We will approach quantum error correction from an angle more familiar to physicist, that of 
ground states of Hamiltonians. There are some proposed [40] implementations of quantum 
computing which have been considered which ef f ectively use the degenerate ground state 
space of a certain multi-qubit Hamiltonian to encode quantum information and protect it 
from noise. Such Hamiltonians look like 
H = â

where each gjis some tensor product of n qubit Paulis; gjâ Pn9operators, e.g. X â

= 0. Note that since each term is commuting, we can describe the

|Ïcodei Nnâk 
j=1 |gji.If our Hamiltonian has n â k such commuting terms, then we have 
specif i ed nâk eigenvalues out of a maximally commuting set of observables of n Paulis, then 
we ef f ectively have k observables left to specify in order to fully specify a unique eigenstates. 
The âvacant spaceâ left in the Hilbert space is what is used to encode information, hence 
in the above case there is a possibility to encode k qubits in the degenerate ground state, 
which is what we express as |Ïcodei. 
Such systems are part of a more general scheme for quantum error correction in quantum 
computing (theory describing how to correct for decoherence in quantum systems) called 
the stabilizer formalism [24]. The rough idea is that a certain class of states are eigenstates 
of tensor products of Paulis on n qubits. For such states, we can specify which n-qubit 
Paulis for which they are a (+1)-eigenvalue eigenstate, and the group generated by products 
of powers of these Paulis is called the Stabilizer group of a given state (for any element of 
the stabilizer group, the state is a +1 eigenvalue eigenstate.

Thus instead of working with the state in Dirac notation, we can simply work with 
the operators for which a state is the +1 eigenvalue eigenstate. Since each Pauli can be 
specif i ed as â¼ XaZb, a,b â Z2, 
then there are 2n bits to specify to describe each such state. 
The set of unitary transformations which map tensor products of Paulis to tensor products 
of Paulis is called the Clif f ord group. In this sense, the stabilizer states are very much like 
Gaussian states, but for discrete variables, the Clif f ord group, as represented on the vector 
space of 2n-bit strings (which themselves represent a state) is isomorphic to the symplectic 
group on 2n bits, Sp(2n,Z2). In contrast, the group of Gaussian transformations on the 
phase space of n harmonic oscillators is Sp(2n,R). We will draw many parallels between 
continuous-variable Gaussian states and stabilizer states of qubits to some gain information 
theoretic intuition.ChatGPTChatGPTIn this section, the thesis discusses quantum error correction, a vital concept in quantum computing, particularly focusing on the relationship between Hamiltonians, subspaces, and quantum error correction techniques. Let's break down these concepts:2.5 Quantum Error CorrectionBasic ConceptPurpose: Quantum error correction involves protecting quantum information from errors due to decoherence and other quantum noise. It's about encoding quantum information in specific subspaces of a Hilbert space to shield it from disturbances.From Hamiltonians to SubspacesGround States of Hamiltonians: The approach taken here relates to the ground states of Hamiltonians in quantum mechanics. In some quantum computing implementations, the degenerate ground state space of a multi-qubit Hamiltonian is used to encode and protect quantum information.Hamiltonian Formulation: The Hamiltonians considered have commuting terms, each a tensor product of qubit Paulis. The ground state of such Hamiltonians can be described as a product of eigenstates of these Pauli operators, with some portion of the Hilbert space left for encoding information.Quantum Error Correction and Stabilizer FormalismStabilizer Formalism: This is a method for quantum error correction where certain quantum states (stabilizer states) are eigenstates of tensor products of Pauli operators. The stabilizer group consists of these Pauli products, and states in this group are stable against certain types of errors.Encoding Information: The space left in the Hilbert space, after specifying eigenstates of the stabilizer group, is used for encoding quantum information. This space can encode a number of qubits depending on the number of commuting terms in the Hamiltonian.Clifford and Symplectic GroupsClifford Group: The set of unitary transformations that map tensor products of Paulis to other tensor products of Paulis. Stabilizer states are closely related to the Clifford group, similar to Gaussian states but for discrete variables.Isomorphism with Symplectic Group: The Clifford group's action on bit strings (representing quantum states) is isomorphic to the symplectic group's action on a phase space, drawing a parallel between continuous-variable Gaussian states and stabilizer states of qubits.Simplifying AnalogiesQuantum Error Correction as a Safe: Think of quantum error correction like using a safe to protect valuable items (quantum information). The safe's structure (subspace of the Hilbert space) is designed to protect against specific threats (quantum noise and decoherence).Hamiltonians and Building Foundations: The role of Hamiltonians in quantum error correction is akin to building a foundation for a house. Just as the foundation determines the structure and stability of the house, the Hamiltonian's ground state space determines how quantum information is encoded and protected.Stabilizer Formalism and Musical Harmony: The stabilizer formalism can be compared to creating a musical harmony. Each note (Pauli operator) contributes to a stable and harmonious chord (stabilizer state). When played together, they create a sound (quantum state) that is resilient to dissonance (errors).These explanations help to understand the fundamental concepts of quantum error correction and their importance in maintaining the integrity of quantum information in computational processes.YouQuantum error correction is a mathematical theory that deals with protecting quantum information from errors and decoherence. Although it is not directly addressed in the main body of the thesis, there are parallels between the concepts underlying quantum error correction and the topics discussed later in the thesis.

One approach to quantum error correction is through the perspective of ground states of Hamiltonians, which is more familiar to physicists. Certain implementations of quantum computing utilize the degenerate ground state space of a multi-qubit Hamiltonian to encode quantum information and protect it from noise. These Hamiltonians have a specific form where each term is a tensor product of n-qubit Pauli operators, and the terms commute with each other. The ground state of such a Hamiltonian can be described as the tensor product of pure +1 eigenvalue eigenstates of each term, along with an arbitrary state for the rest of the Hilbert space. The "vacant space" left in the Hilbert space is used to encode information, allowing for the possibility of encoding k qubits in the degenerate ground state.

This approach is part of a broader scheme for quantum error correction called the stabilizer formalism. In the stabilizer formalism, certain states are eigenstates of tensor products of Pauli operators on n qubits. The group generated by products of powers of these Pauli operators is called the stabilizer group of a given state. Instead of working with the state in Dirac notation, one can work with the operators for which the state is the +1 eigenvalue eigenstate. Each Pauli operator can be specified as a combination of X and Z operators, and thus there are 2n bits needed to specify each stabilizer state.

The set of unitary transformations that map tensor products of Pauli operators to tensor products of Pauli operators is called the Clifford group. The stabilizer states are analogous to Gaussian states in continuous-variable quantum systems, but for discrete variables. The Clifford group, as represented on the space of 2n-bit strings, is isomorphic to the symplectic group on 2n bits, denoted as Sp(2n, Z2). This parallels the group of Gaussian transformations on the phase space of n harmonic oscillators, which is Sp(2n, R). By drawing parallels between continuous-variable Gaussian states and stabilizer states of qubits, one can gain intuition from information theory.

Overall, the use of ground states of Hamiltonians and the stabilizer formalism provide a framework for understanding and implementing quantum error correction, which is crucial for mitigating the effects of decoherence and protecting quantum information in quantum computing systems.ChatGPTChatGPTYour summary captures the essence of the quantum error correction theory and its application in quantum computing, particularly emphasizing the stabilizer formalism and the use of Hamiltonians. Let's highlight the key points for a comprehensive understanding:Quantum Error Correction OverviewPurpose: Quantum error correction is fundamental in protecting quantum information from errors and decoherence, which are common challenges in quantum computing.Mathematical Foundation: It's a mathematical theory that focuses on encoding quantum information in a way that makes it resistant to noise.Hamiltonians and Ground StatesEncoding via Hamiltonians: A practical approach to quantum error correction involves using the ground states of Hamiltonians. These states are particularly stable and can be used to securely store quantum information.Form of Hamiltonians: The Hamiltonians are structured with terms that are tensor products of Pauli operators on multiple qubits. Crucially, these terms commute with each other.Stabilizer FormalismRole: This formalism is a broader scheme within quantum error correction. It involves identifying states that are stable (eigenstates) under specific quantum operations (Pauli tensor products).Stabilizer Group: The stabilizer group is formed by the products of powers of these Pauli operators. States within this group are stable against specific types of quantum errors.Representation and Clifford GroupRepresentation: In the stabilizer formalism, states are often represented by the operators they stabilize, rather than in the traditional Dirac notation.Clifford Group: This is a set of unitary transformations that map tensor products of Pauli operators to other tensor products of Pauli operators. Stabilizer states are closely related to the Clifford group.Analogies to Gaussian StatesComparison: Stabilizer states in discrete variable systems (qubits) are analogous to Gaussian states in continuous-variable systems (like harmonic oscillators).Symplectic Group Parallel: The Clifford group action on bit strings (representing quantum states) is isomorphic to the action of the symplectic group on the phase space, illustrating a parallel between discrete and continuous quantum systems.Importance in Quantum ComputingProtecting Information: Quantum error correction is critical for maintaining the integrity and reliability of quantum information in quantum computing systems.Mitigating Decoherence: It provides a means to counteract the effects of decoherence, a major obstacle in the development of practical quantum computing technologies.Your understanding of these topics lays a solid foundation for grasping the more advanced concepts discussed later in the thesis, particularly those relating to quantum information theory and quantum computing methodologies.You2.5.2Skew Subspaces

Let's simplify these ideas:2.5.2 Skew SubspacesBasic Concept of Skew SubspacesFactorizing Hilbert Space: Quantum error correction involves dividing the overall Hilbert space (the space of all quantum states) into a product of smaller, individual spaces called skew subspaces.Skewness: These subspaces are termed 'skew' because they are oriented differently from the physical factorization of the Hilbert space. They are based on the eigenspaces of stabilizer generators, which often involve more than one physical qubit, hence the skewness or non-alignment with individual qubit spaces.Stabilizer Generators and Hilbert SpaceRepresentation: Instead of representing the Hilbert space as a product of spaces each corresponding to a single qubit, it's represented as a product of spaces each corresponding to a stabilizer generator (HgjH_gjHgâj).Commuting Observables: The factorization in quantum error correction is based on sets of commuting observables. Commuting observables are ones that, when measured together, don't interfere with each other's outcomes.Phase Space and Symplectic Inner ProductCommutation and Orthogonality: In the phase space representation, the commutation relation between Pauli operators is seen as a symplectic inner product. When operators commute, they are orthogonal in terms of this symplectic product.Phase Space Construction: The overall phase space (Î\GammaÎ) can be constructed as a direct sum of orthogonal components (Îgj\Gamma_{gj}Îgjâ) corresponding to each skew subspace.Relevance to Quantum Field TheoryHilbert Space Factorization in QFT: This concept of Hilbert space factorization into skew subspaces will be revisited in discussions of quantum field theory, particularly when dealing with probes interacting with a field.Handling Decoherence: In quantum error correction, and by extension in this thesis, the focus is on handling subsystems and algebras of observables affected by decoherence. The thesis explores how coupling external systems to a quantum field impacts information and subsystems within that field.Simplifying AnalogiesSkew Subspaces as Library Sections:Imagine a library organized not by individual book genres (single qubits) but by collections of genres (stabilizer generators). Each section (skew subspace) contains books (quantum states) from multiple genres that collectively create a broader category. This unconventional organization represents the skew subspaces in the Hilbert space.Phase Space and Symplectic Inner Product as a Puzzle:The phase space can be thought of as a puzzle, where each piece (subspace) fits together with others based on specific rules (commutation relations). The symplectic inner product determines how these pieces are oriented relative to each other, ensuring they fit together perfectly without overlapping (commuting).These simplified explanations and analogies help to conceptualize skew subspaces and their role in quantum error correction, providing a foundational understanding for more complex discussions in quantum field theory and quantum information science.YouIn this section we discuss the structure of correlations and entanglement of stabilizer states 
which will give us some intuition for some of our later work.

By finding a specific choice of generators for the stabilizer group that bridge parts of the Hilbert space (such as AAA and BBB), the entanglement entropy can be calculated simply by counting these bridging generators.Simplifying AnalogiesStabilizer States as a Secure Network:Imagine a stabilizer state as a secure network. The stabilizer group is like a set of rules or protocols that keep the network stable. The normalizer set contains operations that comply with these rules, while the anti-commutator set contains operations that disrupt them.Correlation as Telephone Lines:Correlators in stabilizer states are like telephone lines between two points (qubits or sets of qubits). If the line (correlator) goes through the normalizer, the call (information) goes through. If it goes through the anti-commutator set, the line is cut, and no information is transmitted.Entanglement as Bridges Between Islands:For entanglement in stabilizer states, think of two separate islands (qubit sets AAA and BBB). To create a connection (entanglement) between them, you need bridges (stabilizer elements). The number and structure of these bridges tell you about the entanglement between the islands.These explanations and analogies help to conceptualize the intricate nature of stabilizer states in quantum computing, highlighting their importance in understanding quantum correlations and entanglement.YouTo further understand the structure of entanglement of stabilizer states, let us cover a

This construction involves decomposing the stabilizer group into its individual generators and applying specific mappings to each generator.

The construction begins by considering a maximally entangled state of two qubits, denoted as |Î¦+i â¼ |00i + |11i, which is stabilized by the operator hXX,ZZi. It is noted that any map between Pauli operators that preserves their commutation relations can be implemented by a Clifford circuit. The stabilizer group is projected onto subsystem A, resulting in a new stabilizer group denoted as S|A.

A specific Clifford unitary, denoted as UA, is defined to map S|A onto a new stabilizer group denoted as ËS|A. The mapping is defined as follows: for each generator gk in S|A, UA maps it to Zk; for each negated generator Â¯gk in S|A, UA maps it to Xk; and for each qubit ai in subsystem A, UA maps it to ZËi. This mapping results in |SA| single-qubit states in the |0i state stabilized by Z and |SAB|/2 qubits that require stabilization by both X and Z, hence they are maximally mixed states (XIX = I, ZIZ = I).

A similar construction can be done for subsystem B using a Clifford unitary denoted as UB. The combined mapping U = UA â UB is then defined, and the transformed stabilizer group is denoted as ËS. The resulting state has |SAB/2| Bell pairs (qubit pairs with stabilizers XX,ZZ), and the remaining qubits are tensor products of pure |0i states. The entanglement entropy of the state is given by |SAB|/2.

This construction demonstrates that if there is entanglement between stabilizer states due to the choice of stabilizer generators crossing the bipartition of the Hilbert space, there exists a specific choice of stabilizer generators that allows for the extraction of entanglement entropy. This choice of generators also leads to a factorization of the state into a direct product of Bell pairs. This factorization can be considered equivalent to finding the Schmidt basis of the state. Furthermore, it is mentioned that there is a Clifford transformation that can be applied to achieve this factorization.ChatGPTChatGPTYour summary accurately captures the essence of the construction using Clifford unitaries for mapping and analyzing the entanglement in stabilizer states.
