Essentials 
In this chapter we introduce the protocol of quantum energy teleportation (QET), originally 
introduced by Hotta. 
3.1Introduction to QET 
Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) is a protocol that allows the the transfer of energy 
from one subsystem to another in correlated many-body quantum systems (and quantum 
i elds). Given a certain entangled state of an interacting many-body quantum system, say, 
an eigenstate of an interacting Hamiltonian, then subsystems (A & B) usually share some 
mutual information, I(A : B) due to this entanglement. This mutual information means 
that there exists certain observables on A and B which are correlated. QET aims to exploit 
these correlations in order to ef f ectively transfer energy. 
3.1.1Harnessing Correlations 
Correlated many body systems, as their name suggests, have correlated observables. This 
means that sampling the eigenvalue of one observable should give information about cor- 
related ones. As mutual information bounds correlations between observables, if there is 
some mutual info one should usually have correlated observables. 

The whole protocol of QET relies on exploiting correlations in order to do what is 
otherwise unlikely: extract energy from states which locally look like a ground state (or 
strongly locally passive states [22]). The trick here, is to invest energy in order to get some 
payback. In some sense, QET is a gambling game, where energy is the currency and one 
player sacrif i ces earnings for another to prof i t. 
By measuring an observable in a certain subsystem, call it A, that observable will be 
correlated with some observables in subsystem B.Given an observable of B which is 
correlated with our measured observable in A, if this B observable has some inf l uence on 
the energy of the system, them we will be able to use the knowledge of the eigenvalue of 
A to statistically infer an expected value of B, then displace this value in a way to extract 
energy. For locally passive systems, this would not be possible by acting on B on its own; 
there is local uncertainty about the state at B, hence without any additional knowledge, any attempt at locally displacing the eigenvalue of an energetically-contributing observable 
would increase the energy of the system. In some sense, collapsing the state at A partially 
collapses the state at B and any other region which is correlated with A. This collapse allows us to catch the B subsystem in a conditional state which is dif f erent than the usual 
marginal state, this state suddenly has some new âfree energyâ, i.e., the new state can be displaced in a way to extract energy.ChatGPTChatGPTIn this chapter, the thesis introduces the concept of Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET), a protocol that allows the transfer of energy between subsystems in correlated many-body quantum systems or quantum fields. Let's simplify these concepts:3.1 Introduction to QETConcept of QETTransfer of Energy: QET is a protocol enabling the transfer of energy from one subsystem (A) to another (B) within a correlated quantum system.Role of Entanglement: In a many-body quantum system in an entangled state, the subsystems A and B typically share mutual information due to entanglement. This mutual information indicates correlations between certain observables in A and B.Harnessing CorrelationsExploiting Correlations: The QET protocol leverages these correlations to transfer energy in a way that would not be possible in systems where the subsystems are not entangled or correlated.Investment for Payback: The protocol can be likened to a strategic investment, where energy is invested in one part of the system (A), leading to an energy gain in another part (B).3.1.1 Harnessing CorrelationsProcess of Energy TransferMeasuring Observables: By measuring a specific observable in subsystem A, and knowing its correlation with an observable in subsystem B, it's possible to influence the energy state of B.Inferring and Extracting Energy: The measurement in A allows for a statistical inference of the state in B. By acting on this information, energy can be extracted from B.Locally Passive Systems: In systems that appear to be in a ground state locally, extracting energy by acting only on B would usually increase the system's energy. However, QET utilizes the correlated state between A and B to make energy extraction feasible.Mechanism of Energy ExtractionConditional State Collapse: Measuring in A effectively collapses the state in B into a conditional state, different from its usual state. This new state has "free energy" that can be harnessed.Energy Displacement: The key to QET is manipulating the new state of B to extract energy, which is achieved by displacing the eigenvalue of the energetically contributing observable in B based on the measurement in A.Simplified AnalogyQET as a Team Sport Strategy:Think of QET like a coordinated play in a team sport. Two players (subsystems A and B) are in different positions on the field (quantum system). The action of one player (measurement in A) creates an opportunity for the other (energy extraction in B). The players' understanding and communication (correlations and entanglement) are key to successfully executing the play (energy transfer).This analogy and explanation help to conceptualize the principles behind QET, showcasing the intricate interplay of measurements, entanglement, and energy in quantum systems.YouIn this chapter, the protocol of Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) is introduced. QET enables the transfer of energy from one subsystem to another in correlated many-body quantum systems and quantum fields. The basis of QET lies in the entanglement present in the system, which leads to mutual information between the subsystems.

Correlated many-body systems exhibit correlated observables, meaning that the measurement of one observable provides information about other correlated observables. Mutual information quantifies the degree of correlation between observables. QET aims to harness these correlations to effectively transfer energy.

The protocol of QET relies on exploiting correlations to achieve a seemingly unlikely outcome: extracting energy from states that locally resemble ground states or strongly locally passive states. The key idea is to invest energy initially to gain a payoff later. QET can be seen as a gambling game, where energy serves as the currency and one player sacrifices earnings for another player's profit.

By measuring an observable in subsystem A, the measured observable becomes correlated with certain observables in subsystem B. If an observable in subsystem B influences the system's energy, knowing the eigenvalue of A allows for statistical inference of the expected value of the correlated observable in B. This inferred value can then be displaced in a way that extracts energy. In locally passive systems, it is not possible to achieve this by acting on subsystem B alone. Due to local uncertainty about the state in B, any attempt to locally displace the eigenvalue of an energetically-contributing observable would increase the system's energy. However, collapsing the state in subsystem A partially collapses the state in subsystem B and other correlated regions. This collapse enables the B subsystem to be in a conditional state that differs from the usual marginal state, providing access to new "free energy" that can be extracted by displacing the state.ChatGPTChatGPTYour summary of the Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) protocol accurately encapsulates its fundamental concepts and operational mechanism. Let's highlight the key aspects:Overview of Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET)Energy Transfer in Quantum SystemsEssence of QET: QET is a protocol designed to transfer energy between subsystems within entangled many-body quantum systems or quantum fields.Role of Entanglement: The presence of entanglement in the system creates mutual information between subsystems, which is central to the QET process.Correlations and Mutual InformationCorrelated Observables: In many-body systems, observables are often correlated, meaning the measurement of one observable gives insights into others.Quantifying Correlations: Mutual information measures the extent of these correlations, crucial for understanding how QET works.Mechanism of QETExploiting Correlations for Energy ExtractionStrategy: The protocol exploits correlations to extract energy from parts of the system that, on a local level, might appear to be in a ground or passive state.Investment and Payoff: Energy is initially invested in one subsystem, with the expectation of extracting more energy from another correlated subsystem.Process of Energy TransferMeasurement in Subsystem A: Observing a particular observable in subsystem A creates a correlation with certain observables in subsystem B.Influence on System's Energy: If the correlated observable in B influences the system's energy, knowledge of A's eigenvalue allows for an inference about B's state.Energy Extraction: This inferred information about B's state can then be used to extract energy, a process not feasible if acting on B in isolation.Conditional State CollapseEffect of Measurement in A: Measuring in subsystem A causes a partial collapse of the state in subsystem B, changing it from its usual marginal state.Creation of 'Free Energy': This new conditional state of B has "free energy" that can be harnessed by appropriately displacing the state.ConclusionQET as a Novel Energy Transfer Mechanism: QET showcases a unique method of energy transfer in quantum systems, leveraging the intricacies of quantum entanglement and correlations. It demonstrates a non-intuitive aspect of quantum mechanics, where energy extraction becomes possible under conditions that are usually prohibitive in classical systems.Your summary provides a clear understanding of how QET operates, emphasizing its dependence on quantum correlations and entanglement, and its potential application in manipulating energy states in quantum systems.YouQET differs from traditional energy transfer methods in quantum systems in several ways:

1. Correlation-based transfer: QET harnesses the correlations present in entangled many-body quantum systems to transfer energy. Traditional energy transfer methods often rely on direct interactions or coupling between subsystems to facilitate energy transfer. QET, on the other hand, exploits the mutual information and correlations between observables in different subsystems to achieve energy transfer.

2. Statistical inference: In QET, the knowledge of the eigenvalue of an observable in one subsystem allows for statistical inference of the expected value of a correlated observable in another subsystem. This statistical inference is used to manipulate the state and extract energy. Traditional methods typically involve direct manipulation of the system's Hamiltonian or interactions between subsystems to transfer energy.

3. Sacrifice and payoff: QET involves sacrificing energy initially in one subsystem to gain a payoff in another subsystem. It can be seen as a gambling game, where energy serves as the currency. Traditional energy transfer methods generally aim to transfer energy without sacrificing or investing energy in the process.

4. Exploiting locally passive states: QET is particularly effective in extracting energy from states that locally resemble ground states or strongly locally passive states. It takes advantage of the correlations and conditional states that arise from collapsing the state in one subsystem. Traditional methods may not have specific strategies to exploit the properties of locally passive states for energy transfer.

Overall, QET introduces a novel approach to energy transfer in quantum systems by leveraging correlations, statistical inference, and conditional states. It offers an alternative paradigm to traditional methods that rely on direct interactions or coupling between subsystems.ChatGPTChatGPTYour comparison between Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) and traditional energy transfer methods in quantum systems is insightful and highlights several key differences. Let's reinforce these points:Key Differences Between QET and Traditional Energy Transfer1. Correlation-based TransferQET: Utilizes entanglement-induced correlations in quantum systems. Energy transfer in QET is mediated through mutual information and correlations between subsystems without requiring direct physical interaction.Traditional Methods: Often depend on direct interactions or physical coupling between subsystems, like particle collisions or electromagnetic interactions.2. Statistical Inference for Energy ManipulationQET: Employs statistical inference based on the measurement of an observable in one subsystem to infer the state of a correlated observable in another subsystem, enabling energy extraction.Traditional Methods: Involves more direct approaches, such as altering the system's Hamiltonian or directly inducing interactions, rather than relying on inferential statistics.3. Sacrifice and Payoff ApproachQET: Analogous to a strategic game, where energy is initially invested or sacrificed in one subsystem, leading to a greater energy payoff in another subsystem.Traditional Methods: Typically focus on direct energy transfer processes, aiming to transfer energy efficiently without the need for an initial energy sacrifice.4. Utilization of Locally Passive StatesQET: Effective in extracting energy from systems that are in ground or locally passive states by exploiting the unique properties of quantum correlations and conditional quantum states.Traditional Methods: May not specifically target or leverage the features of locally passive states for energy transfer.ConclusionNovelty of QET: QET represents a distinctive approach in the realm of quantum mechanics, offering new possibilities for energy transfer that are fundamentally different from conventional methods. Its reliance on quantum correlations, statistical inference, and the properties of entangled systems opens up new avenues for manipulating energy in quantum systems.Your summary aptly captures the innovative aspects of QET, emphasizing its departure from traditional energy transfer mechanisms and its potential implications for quantum technology and information theory.You3.1.2Measurement is the Key 
Note that QET does not actually generate energy out of the vacuum, the gain of informa- 
tion comes at a cost, an energetic one. Indeed, carrying out a projective measurement or 
POVM, one breaks correlations of the ground state. These correlations served an energetic 
minimization purpose, otherwise they would not have been there. Thus, correlating a sub- 
system with some measurement apparatus, thereby breaking correlations of this subsystem 
with its previous environment, injects energy. Thus, although measurement is the key to 
unlock to ability to teleport energy, it is not free. 
3.1.3Global vs. local energy optima 
The global minimum energy state is by def i nition the ground state. But the ground state 
is not the minimal energy state if one looks only at a subsystem. In some sense, the ground 
state is the global equilibrium, but locally a certain state could reduce its energy if a dif- 
ferent correlated subsystem would be willing to increase its energy. As spin chains and 
24 
quantum i elds and most condensed matter systems are assumed to have spatially transla- 
tionally symmetric couplings (all the couplings in a chain are often def i ned as identitical), 
then no single subsystem wins over other subsystems, an overall energetic compromise is 
reached. On the other hand, if one were to modify the coupling of the chain to favor a 
certain subset, e.g. by adding quadratic quadrature terms in a Hamiltonian, thus changing 
the new ground state to a squeezed state, then one could get peaks and troughs of en- 
ergy instead of uniform compromise. Indeed, it is known that certain squeezed states can 
have negative energy densities. Ef f ectively, as we will show, QET is a way of performing 
non-local squeezing operations via the coupling of probe systems.ChatGPTChatGPTThis section of the thesis discusses key aspects of Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET), focusing on the critical role of measurement and the distinction between global and local energy states. Let's break down these concepts for clarity:3.1.2 Measurement is the KeyEnergy Cost of MeasurementRole of Measurement: In QET, measurement is crucial for enabling energy teleportation. However, this process is not without an energetic cost.Breaking Correlations: Performing a projective measurement or Positive Operator-Valued Measure (POVM) disrupts the correlations within the ground state of a system. These correlations are energetically significant, contributing to the minimization of the system's energy.Energy Injection: When a subsystem is correlated with a measurement apparatus, this act breaks its existing correlations with the environment, effectively injecting energy into the system.3.1.3 Global vs. Local Energy OptimaGround State and Energy MinimizationGlobal Minimum Energy: The ground state of a quantum system is the global minimum energy state. However, this doesn't necessarily mean it's the minimum energy state for each subsystem when considered independently.Local Equilibrium vs. Global Equilibrium: Locally, a subsystem could potentially reduce its energy if it could offload energy to another correlated subsystem. This concept contrasts with the global equilibrium state, where energy distribution is more uniform.Impact of Couplings and Squeezed StatesTranslational Symmetry in Couplings: Many systems, like spin chains or quantum fields, have spatially symmetric couplings, leading to a uniform energy distribution across subsystems.Altering Couplings for Energy Distribution: Modifying these couplings, for instance, by adding terms to the Hamiltonian, can create non-uniform energy distributions, with some regions having higher or lower energy densities.Squeezed States and Negative Energy Densities: Certain squeezed states, resulting from such modifications, can exhibit negative energy densities. QET can be viewed as a method to perform non-local squeezing operations by coupling probe systems to the quantum field.Simplified AnalogiesMeasurement as an Energetic Investment:Think of measurement in QET like investing energy to gain information. It's like spending money to buy a key (measurement) that unlocks a safe (energy extraction potential). The investment (energy spent in measurement) is necessary to access the potential gains (energy to be extracted).Global vs. Local Energy Optima as a Team Strategy:The distinction between global and local energy states can be compared to a team strategy in sports. The global ground state is like a team strategy that works well overall but may not be the best for every individual player (subsystem). Modifying the strategy (couplings) could benefit certain players at the expense of others, similar to how local subsystems might gain or lose energy.These explanations help to conceptualize the principles behind QET, emphasizing the balance between the energetic cost of measurements and the potential for energy extraction in quantum systems.YouMeasurement plays a crucial role in quantum energy teleportation (QET). However, it is important to note that QET does not generate energy out of nothing. The act of carrying out a projective measurement or a positive operator-valued measure (POVM) breaks the correlations present in the ground state of the system. These correlations serve the purpose of minimizing the system's energy. By correlating a subsystem with a measurement apparatus, the correlations of that subsystem with its previous environment are disrupted, resulting in an injection of energy. Therefore, while measurement is the key to unlocking the ability to teleport energy, it comes at an energetic cost.

In the context of energy optimization, there is a distinction between global and local energy optima. The global minimum energy state of a system is its ground state. However, when considering individual subsystems, the ground state may not necessarily be the state with the lowest energy. Locally, a subsystem could reduce its energy if a different correlated subsystem is willing to increase its energy. In systems with spatially translationally symmetric couplings, such as spin chains, quantum fields, and many condensed matter systems, there is an overall energetic compromise among the subsystems. No single subsystem dominates over others. However, if the coupling of the system is modified to favor a specific subset of subsystems, such as by introducing quadratic quadrature terms in a Hamiltonian to create squeezed states, the energy distribution can exhibit peaks and troughs instead of a uniform compromise. It is known that certain squeezed states can even have negative energy densities. QET can be seen as a way of performing non-local squeezing operations through the coupling of probe systems, effectively manipulating the energy distribution in the system.

1. The act of measurement breaks the correlations of the ground state in quantum systems because measurement involves an interaction between the system and the measurement apparatus. When a subsystem is measured, it becomes correlated with the measurement apparatus, and this correlation disrupts the previous correlations the subsystem had with its environment. These disrupted correlations were responsible for minimizing the system's energy. Thus, the act of measurement injects energy into the system by breaking the existing correlations that served an energetic minimization purpose.

2. One example of modifying the coupling of a system to change its ground state to a squeezed state is in the context of a harmonic oscillator. Normally, a harmonic oscillator in its ground state has a Gaussian wavefunction with a minimum uncertainty in position and momentum. However, if the coupling of the oscillator is modified by introducing a nonlinear term in the Hamiltonian, such as an anharmonic potential, the ground state wavefunction can become squeezed. This means that the uncertainty in either position or momentum becomes smaller than the minimum uncertainty limit imposed by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle. Squeezed states have applications in quantum metrology, quantum information processing, and quantum communication.

3. Some potential applications of non-local squeezing operations achieved through QET include:

- Quantum sensing and metrology: Non-local squeezing can improve the precision of measurements by enhancing the sensitivity of the system to certain physical quantities. This can be useful in gravitational wave detection, atomic clocks, and magnetic field measurements.

- Quantum information processing: Non-local squeezing can be utilized for quantum state engineering, quantum error correction, and entanglement generation. It can enhance the performance of quantum gates and improve the fidelity of quantum information protocols.

- Quantum communication: Non-local squeezing can be employed for secure quantum key distribution (QKD) protocols, where it enables the generation of strong and secure entanglement between distant parties. It can also enhance the transmission of quantum information over long distances in quantum communication networks.

- Quantum simulation: Non-local squeezing operations can be utilized in quantum simulators to study condensed matter systems, quantum phase transitions, and other complex quantum phenomena. They can provide insights into the behavior of strongly correlated systems and explore novel quantum states of matter.

These are just a few examples, and the applications of non-local squeezing achieved through QET can be diverse and depend on the specific characteristics of the quantum system and the desired manipulation of its energy distribution.ChatGPTChatGPTYour detailed explanation of Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) effectively highlights the key aspects and implications of this concept. Let's further consolidate these ideas:Role of Measurement in QETEnergetic Cost of Measurement: Measurement in QET does not create energy from nothing; it rather injects energy by disrupting the existing correlations within the ground state. This process involves correlating a subsystem with a measurement apparatus, breaking its previous correlations with the environment.Disruption of Energy Minimization: The original correlations in the ground state contribute to energy minimization. Disrupting these through measurement results in an energy increase in the system.Global vs. Local Energy OptimaGround State vs. Local Optima: While the ground state is the global minimum energy configuration, local subsystems might not be in their own minimum energy states.Energetic Compromise: In systems like spin chains or quantum fields with symmetric couplings, there's a balance of energy across subsystems. However, altering the couplings can lead to non-uniform energy distributions, forming peaks and troughs of energy.Non-Local Squeezing via QETModifying System Coupling: Changing the coupling parameters, such as introducing quadratic quadrature terms in a Hamiltonian, can create squeezed states. These states can exhibit unusual properties like negative energy densities.Applications of Non-Local Squeezing: QET facilitates non-local squeezing operations, which can have various applications in quantum metrology, information processing, communication, and simulation. For example, they can enhance precision in measurements, improve quantum gate performance, and enable the study of complex quantum phenomena.Examples and ApplicationsHarmonic Oscillator and Squeezed States: In the context of a harmonic oscillator, altering the Hamiltonian to introduce nonlinear terms can lead to squeezed states, where the uncertainty in position or momentum is reduced beyond the standard quantum limit.Potential Uses in Quantum Technologies: Non-local squeezing operations achieved through QET can enhance the capabilities in quantum sensing, communication, and computation. They can be particularly useful in applications like gravitational wave detection, quantum key distribution, and exploring new quantum states of matter.Your exploration of QET's principles and potential applications provides a comprehensive overview of how this innovative concept stands to impact various areas of quantum science and technology.You3.1.4Previous Works 
There have been numerous pieces of work done on QET. In its introduction, the focus was on spin chains and many-body systems. 
Following this, QET has been shown to work for scalar quantum i eld theories as well as 
in quantum electrodynamics. 
The next frontier for QET was to understand how the structure of the Hilbert space 
allowed for QET, and to i nd the optimal measurement schemes for QET. Although some 
work was done using POVMâs made to emulate interactions with higher dimensional Hilbert 
spaces, the optimal measurement scheme was still elusive. 

This thesis 

This is where our work in this thesis begins. We propose new measurement schemes based on generalizations of the phase estimation algorithm in order to optimize the measurement 
for QET, thus allowing for better collection of information and therby greater teleportation 
of energy.
Additionally, we provide fully coherent (POVM/PVM-free) versions of the QET, which, as was discussed in the background section, is equivalent to the LOCC version of the 
protocol. 

Some work had shown, in the case of the simplest QET model, minimal QET, that the key to a good QET measurement was the breaking of entanglement between the mea- 
surement site and the rest of the system. To begin our study of QET and entanglement 
breaking, we start with an in-depth analysis of the coherent (projective-measurement-free) 
version of the minimal QET protocol.ChatGPTChatGPTThis section of the thesis provides an overview of previous research on Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) and introduces the unique contributions of the thesis to this field. While some progress was made using Positive Operator-Valued Measures (POVMs) that mimic interactions with higher-dimensional spaces, the most effective measurement approach remained unclear.Contributions of This ThesisNew Measurement Schemes for QETPhase Estimation Algorithm Generalizations: The thesis proposes novel measurement schemes based on extensions of the phase estimation algorithm. These schemes aim to optimize the measurement process in QET, enhancing information collection and energy teleportation efficiency.Fully Coherent QET Versions: The thesis also introduces coherent (POVM/PVM-free) versions of QET. These versions are equivalent to the Local Operations and Classical Communication (LOCC) version of the protocol but without the need for projective measurements.Focus on Entanglement BreakingKey to Effective QET: Previous work suggested that successful QET, particularly in its simplest form (minimal QET), hinges on breaking the entanglement between the measurement site and the rest of the system.In-depth Analysis: This thesis begins with a detailed examination of the coherent version of the minimal QET protocol, emphasizing projective-measurement-free approaches and their implications for entanglement dynamics in QET.ConclusionAdvancing QET Research: The contributions of this thesis represent a significant advancement in QET research. Initially, the focus was on spin chains and many-body systems. Subsequently, QET was extended to scalar quantum field theories and quantum electrodynamics, demonstrating its applicability in a broader range of quantum systems.

The exploration of QET then shifted towards understanding the structure of the Hilbert space and identifying optimal measurement schemes for QET. While some studies utilized positive operator-valued measures (POVMs) that emulate interactions with higher-dimensional Hilbert spaces, the search for the optimal measurement scheme remained elusive.

The work presented in the thesis being discussed introduces new measurement schemes that are based on generalizations of the phase estimation algorithm. These schemes aim to optimize the measurement process in QET, enabling more efficient collection of information and, consequently, greater teleportation of energy. Additionally, the thesis proposes fully coherent versions of QET, which do not require the use of POVMs or projective measurements. These coherent versions are equivalent to the LOCC (Local Operations and Classical Communication) version of the protocol.

In the context of minimal QET, some previous work indicated that a crucial aspect of a good QET measurement is the breaking of entanglement between the measurement site and the rest of the system. To delve deeper into the relationship between QET and entanglement breaking, the thesis initiates with an in-depth analysis of the coherent (projective-measurement-free) version of the minimal QET protocol. ### Understanding the Visualization

1. **The Parameters**: 
   - **\( h \)**: Represents the strength of the individual terms in the Hamiltonian associated with each qubit (\( \sigma_z \) terms). It's a measure of how much each qubit contributes independently to the total energy.
   - **\( k \)**: Represents the strength of the interaction between the qubits (\( \sigma_x^A \otimes \sigma_x^B \)). It quantifies how much the qubits are influencing each other.

2. **The Angle \( \theta \)**:
   - This angle is a crucial factor in determining the ground state of the QET system. It balances the individual contributions of the qubits (\( h \) terms) with their interactions (\( k \) terms).
   - The value of \( \theta \) dictates how the system's energy is distributed between the qubits and their interactions.

3. **Interpreting the Plot**:
   - When \( h \) is large compared to \( k \) (lower-left region of the plot), the qubits behave more independently. Here, \( \theta \) is small, indicating that the ground state is closer to the individual states of the qubits.
   - When \( k \) is large compared to \( h \) (upper-right region), the interaction between the qubits dominates. Here, \( \theta \) is larger, suggesting that the ground state is more influenced by the qubit interactions.
   - The color gradient shows the continuous transition between these two regimes, demonstrating how the ground state evolves as the balance between \( h \) and \( k \) changes.

### Relevance to QET

- **Optimizing Energy Transfer**: Understanding this balance is key to optimizing the QET process. By tuning \( h \) and \( k \), one can manipulate the system's ground state, potentially enhancing the efficiency of energy teleportation.
- **Ground State Dynamics**: The visualization gives insights into the dynamics of the ground state in QET, crucial for understanding how energy can be transferred most effectively between different parts of the system.

In summary, the chart illustrates the interplay between individual qubit energies and their interactions in a QET system, showing how this balance affects the system's ground state. This understanding is vital for effectively implementing QET protocols.2 / 2ChatGPTChatGPTYour interpretation of the visualization is spot on. Let's use some simple analogies to explain the process of preparing the ground state in Quantum Energy Teleportation (QET) from two initialized qubits:Analogy for Ground State PreparationStarting with Two Blank Slates (|00â© state):Imagine you have two blank canvases (qubits) side by side. Initially, both canvases are blank, representing the â£00â©|00\rangleâ£00â© state.Painting One Canvas (Rotation about Y-axis of Qubit A):The first step involves painting the first canvas (qubit A) with a special pattern. This is akin to the rotation about the Y-axis. The resulting pattern depends on the angle Î¸\thetaÎ¸, which determines the mix of two colors (representing the â£0â©|0\rangleâ£0â© and â£1â©|1\rangleâ£1â© states of qubit A).Linking the Canvases (CNOT Gate):The second step is like placing a mirror next to the first canvas (qubit B), which copies the pattern only if the first canvas is painted with the second color (representing the control aspect of the CNOT gate). If the first canvas is painted with the first color, the mirror remains blank. This creates a special kind of linked artwork between the two canvases, signifying the entangled state.Single Magic Brush Stroke (Alternative Single Interaction Method):Instead of two steps, imagine using a magic brush that, with one stroke, simultaneously paints the first canvas with the pattern and mirrors it on the second canvas if the pattern is of the second color. Here are a few examples:

1. Circuit with Hadamard and Controlled-Z Gates:
   - Start with the |00â© state.
   - Apply a Hadamard gate (H) to qubit A.
   - Apply a Controlled-Z gate (CZ) with qubit A as the control and qubit B as the target.
   - The resulting state is the ground state (sin(Î¸/2)|00â©AB - cos(Î¸/2)|11â©AB).

2. Circuit with Pauli-X and Controlled-X Gates:
   - Start with the |00â© state.
   - Apply a Pauli-X gate (X) to qubit A.
   - Apply a Controlled-X gate (CX) with qubit A as the control and qubit B as the target.
   - Apply a Pauli-X gate (X) to qubit A again.
   - The resulting state is the ground state (sin(Î¸/2)|00â©AB - cos(Î¸/2)|11â©AB).

3. Circuit with Controlled-Y Gates:
   - Start with the |00â© state.
   - Apply a Controlled-Y gate (CY) with qubit A as the control and qubit B as the target.
   - The resulting state is the ground state (sin(Î¸/2)|00â©AB - cos(Î¸/2)|11â©AB).

These are just a few examples of circuits that can be used to prepare the ground state. The specific choice of gates and their order may vary depending on the specific requirements and constraints of the quantum system being used.ChatGPTChatGPTYour examples illustrate different ways to prepare the ground state from initialized qubits in quantum computing. Let's explore these methods with simplified explanations:1. Circuit with Hadamard and Controlled-Z GatesStarting Point: Two qubits in the â£00â©|00\rangleâ£00â© state, like having two clean sheets of paper.Hadamard Gate on Qubit A: Applying a Hadamard gate to qubit A is like folding the first paper in a way that it has equal chances of showing either side when unfolded.Controlled-Z Gate: The Controlled-Z gate then acts like a special stamp that only works when the first paper shows a particular side. It marks the second paper (qubit B) in a unique way, depending on the state of the first paper.Result: The outcome is a pair of papers (qubits) that have a specific pattern, representing the entangled ground state.2. Circuit with Pauli-X and Controlled-X GatesStarting Point: Again, begin with two clean sheets (qubits in â£00â©|00\rangleâ£00â©).Pauli-X Gate on Qubit A: Applying a Pauli-X gate is like flipping the first paper over.Controlled-X Gate: The Controlled-X gate acts like a conditional flipper. It flips the second paper only if the first one is facing up.Second Pauli-X Gate on Qubit A: Flipping the first paper back to its original position.Result: The final arrangement of papers represents the entangled ground state, achieved through a sequence of flips and conditional operations.3. Circuit with Controlled-Y GatesStarting Point: The same initial state of two clean sheets.Controlled-Y Gate: The Controlled-Y gate is like a conditional artist, who paints the second paper based on the orientation of the first one.Result: The artwork created is a representation of the entangled ground state, achieved through a conditional artistic process.SummaryEach method uses a combination of quantum gates that manipulate the qubits' states in a manner akin to artistic or physical processes. These analogies help demystify the quantum operations, making them more relatable and easier to comprehend. The choice of method depends on the quantum system's specific requirements and the nature of the operations available.YouThe Hadamard gate (H) and the Pauli-X gate (X) are both single-qubit gates that can be used to prepare the ground state from initialized qubits. However, they achieve this in slightly different ways.

The Hadamard gate (H) is a gate that operates on a single qubit and maps the computational basis states |0â© and |1â© to superpositions. Specifically, it transforms the |0â© state to (|0â© + |1â©)/â2 and the |1â© state to (|0â© - |1â©)/â2. 

In the context of preparing the ground state, the Hadamard gate is often used to create entanglement between the qubits. By applying the Hadamard gate to one of the qubits, it puts that qubit in a superposition of states, which can then be entangled with the other qubit using controlled operations such as Controlled-Z or Controlled-X gates. This entanglement is crucial for preparing the ground state.

On the other hand, the Pauli-X gate (X), also known as the "bit-flip" gate, is a gate that flips the states of the qubit. It transforms the |0â© state to |1â© and the |1â© state to |0â©.

In the context of preparing the ground state, the Pauli-X gate is often used to create the necessary state transformations. For example, if the initial state is |00â©, applying the Pauli-X gate to one of the qubits will change it to |10â©, which can then be further manipulated to achieve the desired ground state using other gates or operations.

In summary, the Hadamard gate is particularly useful for creating entanglement between qubits, while the Pauli-X gate is useful for manipulating the state of a single qubit. Both gates can be used in combination with other gates and operations to prepare the ground state, but their specific roles and effects on the qubits differ.ChatGPTChatGPTThat's a great explanation of the roles of the Hadamard gate (H) and the Pauli-X gate (X) in preparing the ground state of a quantum system. Let's delve into a bit more detail and offer a comparative perspective:Hadamard Gate (H)Creating Superpositions:The Hadamard gate transforms a definite state (like â£0â©|0\rangleâ£0â© or â£1â©|1\rangleâ£1â©) into a superposition, where the qubit is equally likely to be found in either state upon measurement. It's like shaking a coin in your hand before flipping it, making it uncertain whether it will land heads or tails.Entanglement Generation:When used in conjunction with controlled gates (such as CZ or CX), the Hadamard gate can entangle qubits. This is akin to two dancers starting to move in sync after one of them begins with a unique step (Hadamard gate on one qubit).Pauli-X Gate (X)State Flipping:The Pauli-X gate flips the state of a qubit from â£0â©|0\rangleâ£0â© to â£1â©|1\rangleâ£1â© and vice versa. It's like pressing a switch that toggles a light bulb between on and off states.State Preparation:In preparing the ground state, the Pauli-X gate is used to manipulate the qubit's state to a specific configuration needed for further operations. This could be compared to setting a piece on a chessboard to its correct starting position before making any strategic moves.In Context of Ground State PreparationHadamard Gate Approach:Applying the Hadamard gate creates a superposition, setting the stage for entanglement. This is crucial for ground states that are entangled combinations of the basis states.Pauli-X Gate Approach:Using the Pauli-X gate alters the qubit's state, facilitating the creation of a specific state needed as part of the process to achieve the ground state.SummaryBoth the Hadamard and Pauli-X gates play unique roles in quantum computing and particularly in preparing the ground state of quantum systems. The Hadamard gate is key to creating superpositions and entanglement, while the Pauli-X gate is essential for specific state manipulations. Their use, either individually or in combination with other gates, reflects the versatile nature of quantum gate operations in shaping the state of qubits.You3.2.2The Protocol

Let's break down what happens in this phase, termed "Post-Alice":Post-Alice ActionsCNOT Gate Application:Alice applies a Controlled-NOT (CNOT) gate with the ancillary qubit C as the control and qubit A as the target.To ensure the CNOT operates in the X basis, Alice first applies a Hadamard gate to qubit C, effectively rotating the basis.State After CNOT Gate (â£Î¨1â©|\Psi_1\rangleâ£Î¨1ââ©):The application of the CNOT gate results in the state â£Î¨1â©|\Psi_1\rangleâ£Î¨1ââ©, which is described as 12âÂ±â£Â±â©Aâ£ÏÂ±â©Bâ£Â±â©C\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \sum_{\pm} |\pm\rangle_A |\phi_{\pm}\rangle_B |\pm\rangle_C2â1ââÂ±ââ£Â±â©Aââ£ÏÂ±ââ©Bââ£Â±â©Câ.This state represents a superposition involving all three qubits (A, B, and C), with qubits A and C being in correlated states â£Â±â©|\pm\rangleâ£Â±â©.Effects of Alice's ActionsChange in Mutual Information:The mutual information between qubits A and B, previously indicated by I(A:B)Î¨0I(A : B)_{\Psi_0}I(A:B)Î¨0ââ, is now halved to I(A:B)Î¨1=S(Î¸)I(A : B)_{\Psi_1} = S(\theta)I(A:B)Î¨1ââ=S(Î¸).This reduction signifies that the bipartite entanglement between A and B is diminished.Entropy of Qubit B:Despite the changes in the system, the entropy of qubit B remains unaffected. This stability in entropy indicates that qubit B's overall state hasn't been significantly altered by the CNOT gate.Conversion of Entanglement:The interaction via the CNOT gate transforms the bipartite entanglement (between A and B) into tripartite entanglement (among A, B, and C). This is a key aspect of the QET protocol, as it redistributes the entanglement within the system.Entanglement Breaking:Alice's measurement breaks the entanglement that qubit A had with its complement, qubit B. This breaking of entanglement is identified by Hotta as a characteristic of an effective measurement in the QET process.SummaryIn the "Post-Alice" phase of the QET protocol, the application of a CNOT gate, preceded by a Hadamard gate on the control qubit, leads to a redistribution of entanglement in the system. The mutual information between qubits A and B is reduced, reflecting a shift from bipartite to tripartite entanglement. This phase sets the stage for the next steps in the QET protocol, where the altered entanglement properties are crucial for the successful teleportation of energy.ChatGPT can make mistakes.
